  "text": "We have recently demonstrated that the GPCR adaptor protein, b-arrestin, regulates MDA-MB-231 cell invasiveness [CITATION_1] . In addition, we found that GPR54, which is endogenously expressed in MDA-MB-231 cells, was unable to stimulate ERK1/ 2 activity, upon depletion of b-arrestin 2 [CITATION_2] . This suggests that barrestin 2 is required for GPR54 signaling to ERK1/2. To define a molecular mechanism by which Kp-10 induces breast cancer cell invasiveness, we investigated the effect of depleting b-arrestin 2 on this process. Knockdown of b-arrestin 2 in MDA-MB-231 cells significantly reduced basal invasion in the absence of Kp-10, as well as Kp-10-stimulated invasion, compared with the scrambled control shRNA (Fig. 5A) . Furthermore, we found that depletion of b-arrestin 2 reduced MMP-9 secretion and activity in cells, in the presence or absence of Kp-10, in contrast to cells expressing the scrambled control shRNA (Fig. 5B) . Kp-10-mediated EGFR phosphorylation was also inhibited in b-arrestin 2 knockdown cells, as compared to the scrambled controls, implicating a role for b-arrestin 2 in mediating Kp-10-induced EGFR transactivation (Fig. 5C) . Knockdown of b-arrestin 2 did not affect cell viability as determined by 3-(4,5-dimethylthiazol-2-yl)-2,5-diphenyltetrazolium bromide (MTT) assays (Fig. S1B) . These results reveal that b-arrestin 2 regulates basal and Kp-10-dependent invasion, by regulating MMP-9 secretion and activity.",
